{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20837"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13712"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"11598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11752"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is a condition affecting the distal oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular changes seen in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disordered cellular growth with loss of normal maturation patterns","Replacement of one mature cell type with another mature cell type","Loss of cellular differentiation and structural organisation","Increased number of morphologically normal cells","Increased size of individual cells without increased cell number"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplacement of one mature cell type with another mature cell type\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes metaplasia, which characterises Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. In this condition, the normal stratified squamous epithelium of the distal oesophagus is replaced by columnar epithelium with intestinal features, typically in response to chronic acid exposure from gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisordered cellular growth with loss of normal maturation patterns\u003C/strong\u003E describes dysplasia, which can develop in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus as a precancerous change, but is not the defining characteristic.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of cellular differentiation and structural organisation\u003C/strong\u003E describes anaplasia, typically seen in malignant tumours. Barrett\u0027s oesophagus involves a change to a different differentiated cell type, not dedifferentiation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased number of morphologically normal cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes hyperplasia, which is not the primary change in Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased size of individual cells without increased cell number\u003C/strong\u003E describes hypertrophy, which is not a feature of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is clinically significant because it increases the risk of developing oesophageal adenocarcinoma, with the risk increasing further if dysplasia develops within the metaplastic epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is characterised by metaplasia where normal squamous epithelium is replaced by columnar epithelium.","Metaplasia is a reversible change in which one adult cell type is replaced by another adult cell type.","Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is associated with chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.","It is a risk factor for oesophageal adenocarcinoma."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; 272."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-08T18:03:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-08T18:05:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13712"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"d